"{\"uid\": \"metro.co.uk-2024-07-18-brits-heading-olympics-paris-need-know-this-driving-law-21255740\", \"text\": \"Brits heading to theOlympicsthis year via car could end up with a hefty fine and points on their licence if they do not know this law in France.  As thesummerholidays approach and with theParisOlympics on the horizon, British motorists planning to drive in France are being urged to familiarise themselves with localdrivinglaws.  One of the key regulations that might catch British drivers off guard is the banning of wearing headphones or headsets while driving.  Graham Conway from\\u00a0Select Car Leasing\\u00a0said: 'While many French driving laws mirror those in the UK, some are less familiar to Brits, such as the ban on using ear pieces.'  Modern cars come equipped with advanced sound systems and in-built microphones, making the use of headphones redundant.  Start your day informed with Metro'sNews Updatesnewsletter or getBreaking Newsalerts the moment it happens.  However, drivers of older car models might still resort to headphones for phone calls or listening to podcasts.  Mr Conway has warned against this practice, emphasising the safety risks involved.  He said: 'Not being able to hear your surroundings is incredibly dangerous. You could miss critical sounds like emergency sirens, honking horns, or even nearby cyclists and pedestrians.  'In France, this is not just unsafe but illegal. Being caught can result in a fine of 135 euros (\\u00a3113) and three points on your licence.'  In addition to the headphone ban, there are other French road laws that British drivers might overlook, including the mandatory display of an emissions sticker, known as the Crit'Air vignette, on your vehicle.  This sticker indicates the vehicle's emissions levels and is essential for driving in certain low-emission zones aimed at improving air quality. Failure to display this sticker can lead to a fine of up to 135 euros.  Another significant regulation is the possession of speed camera detectors.  Mr Conway noted: 'Radar or laser detectors, which identify the presence of speed traps, are illegal in France regardless of whether they are in use.  'If found with one, even if it's switched off, you could face a 1,500 euro fine, six points on your licence, and a three-year driving ban.  'Understanding and adhering to local regulations can help ensure a safe and hassle-free trip, avoiding unexpected fines and penalties.  'So if you are planning a trip to France - or any country for that matter - this summer, it is essential you take time to review the local laws.'  Get in touch with our news team by emailing us atwebnews@metro.co.uk.  For more stories like this,check our news page.  ArrowMORE:BA pilot 'filmed himself spanking naked crew member then shared video with pal'  ArrowMORE:Fisherman fined \\u00a32,500 for what he did with a salmon  ArrowMORE:Woman who poisoned girl, 11, while trying to get rid of bedbugs spared jail  Never miss the biggest stories with breaking news alerts in your inbox.  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy\"}"